{{Infobox legislature | name = Central National Committee of the Kingdom of Yugoslavia | native_name = Централни Национални Комитет Краљевине Југославије | native_name_lang = Serbian | transcription_name = | legislature = | coa_pic = | coa_res = | coa_alt = | coa_caption = | logo_pic = | logo_res = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | house_type = | body = | jurisdiction = | houses = | term_limits = | foundation = August or September 1941 | disbanded = April 1945 | preceded_by = [[Dragiša Vasić]] | succeeded_by = | new_session = | leader1_type = vicepresident | leader1 = Mustafa Mulalić (since beginning of 1943) | party1 = | election1 = | leader2_type = secretary of the Executive Board | leader2 = Đura Đurović | party2 = | election2 = | leader3_type = | leader3 = | party3 = | election3 = | leader4_type = | leader4 = | party4 = | election4 = | leader5_type = | leader5 = | party5 = | election5 = | leader6_type = | leader6 = | party6 = | election6 = | leader7_type = | leader7 = | party7 = | election7 = | seats = | house1 = | house2 = | structure1 = | structure1_res = | structure1_alt = | structure2 = | structure2_res = | structure2_alt = | political_groups1 = | political_groups2 = | committees1 = | committees2 = | joint_committees = | term_length = | authority = | salary = | seats1_title = | seats1 = | seats2_title = | seats2 = | seats3_title = | seats3 = | seats4_title = | seats4 = | seats5_title = | seats5 = | seats6_title = | seats6 = | seats7_title = | seats7 = | seats8_title = | seats8 = | voting_system1 = | voting_system2 = | first_election1 = | first_election2 = | first_election3 = | last_election1 = | last_election2 = | last_election3 = | next_election1 = | next_election2 = | next_election3 = | redistricting = | motto = For Democracy, Against All Dictatorships | session_room = | session_res = | session_alt = | meeting_place = | session_room2 = | session_res2 = | session_alt2 = | meeting_place2 = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | constitution = | footnotes = }} The '''Central National Committee of the Kingdom of Yugoslavia'''{{sfn|Lees|2007|p=183}} known also by its Yugoslav abbreviation '''CNK''' ({{lang-sr|Централни Национални Комитет Краљевине Југославије}}){{sfn|Papadopolos|1974|p=649|ps=: "„Veliki narodni kongres" odlučio je da se Centralni nacionalni komitet Kraljevine Jugoslavije proširi i da se pristupi ..."}} was an advisory body of the [[Yugoslav Army in the Fatherland]] (commonly known as the Chetniks) established during the [[WWII]] in August 1941 by the group of political representatives of all prewar opposition parties.
== Background == After the short [[Occupation of Yugoslavia|April War]] in 1941 Axis forces swiftly ocuppied and desintegrated [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]]. A small group of Yugoslav officers led by [[Draža Mihailović]] did not accept capitulation of the Yugoslav Army and organized resistance and their headquarter on Ravna Gora. As soon as the news about this resistance movement reached Belgrade, many intellectuals and members of numerous non-communist political parties supported it.{{sfn|Čubrilović|1974|p=522}} This group of people in Belgrade became a nucleus of CNK which coordinated their activities with rebel headquarter on Ravna Gora.{{sfn|Čubrilović|1974|p=522}}
== Establishment == The CNC was established in the end of August 1941 as consultative body.{{sfn|Matić|Vesović|1995|p=20}} According to some sources, the CNK was established in September 1941.{{sfn|Latas|Dželebdžić|1979|p=43|ps=: "По неким верзијама, до формирања овог комитета дошло је срединой августа, а по некима, у септембру 1941."}}
The Chetniks (Yugoslav Army in Homeland) established the Mountain Staff No. 1 and Central National Committee, making ideological substance of the Chetnk movement - For Democracy, Against All Dictatorships - their aim of the war.<ref name="Congress1989">{{cite book|last=Congress|first=United States.|title=Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the ... Congress|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JkqMZT1s5jUC|year=1989|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|page=5901}}</ref> The CNK was composed of the political representatives of all prewar opposition parties.<ref name="Congress1989" />
The members of its Executive Board were [[Dragiša Vasić]], [[Mladen Žujović|Mladen Mlađa Žujović]] and [[Stevan Moljević]].{{sfn|Vučković|Krstić|2001|p=15}} After some time regional committees were established in [[Montenegro]] ({{lang-sr|Комитет црногорских националиста}}) and in [[Split, Croatia|Split]] ({{lang-sr|Српски национални комитет}}) which were not directly subordinated to the CNK although they supported Mihajlović.<ref>{{cite book|title=Recueil des travaux du Musée national|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kI3JhYflI5UC|year=2007|publisher=Muzej|page=151}}</ref>
== Activities ==
The CNK did not have particular importance.{{sfn|Milićević|2009|p=66|ps=:" Додуше, постојао је, мада без већег значаја, Централни национални комитет као политичко тело још од августа 1941. године. }} For the first two years only its Executive Board was active.{{sfn|Matić|Vesović|1995|p=20}} At the beginning of 1943 the CNC was expanded and joined by Aleksandar Aksentijević, Đuro Đurović, Mustafa Mulalić and Đuro Vilović.{{sfn|Minić|1993|p=191}}
The CNK began with resistance to Axis occupying forces immediatelly after it was established.{{sfn|Марковић|1998|p=110|ps=:"Убрзо је Централни национални комитет, као политички одбор четничког покрета, у Београду почео са активностима на пружању отпора њемачком окупатору."}} [[File:Djura Djurovic wiki photo.jpg|thumb|left|Photo of Đura Đurović, secretary of the Executive Board of CNK and editor of its official organ "Glas Jugoslavije"]]
According to the decisions of the Conference in the village Ba, the CNK was designated to acquire political responsibility and cooperation with Allies until liberation from Fascists and Communists and also with the government of the future Yugoslav Federation composed of three federal units, Serbia, Croatia and Slovenia.<ref>{{cite news |last=Roberts |first= Valter |date= 13 December 2013 |title= Черчилов избор – Броз! |url=http://www.novosti.rs/%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%B0%D1%82%D0%BD%D0%B8_%D1%81%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%80%D0%B6%D0%B0%D1%98.524.html:468393-%D0%A7%D0%B5%D1%80%D1%87%D0%B8%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%B2-%D0%B8%D0%B7%D0%B1%D0%BE%D1%80-%D0%91%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B7 |work= Večernje Novosti |location= |access-date= 9 September 2018 }}</ref> The vicepresident of CNK was [[Mustafa Mulalić]] who hoped to collect all Muslim sympatizers of the Yugoslav Federation as projected by the Chetniks.<ref>{{cite book|title=Djela|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bh71-km-jf0C|year=1987|publisher=Akademija|page=130|quote=Potpredsjednik Centralnog nacionalnog, komiteta ravnogorskog pokreta Mustafa Mulalić još je gajio nadu da bi među ...}}</ref>
The official organ of the CNK was ''Glas Yugoslavije'', initiated on 10 July 1944.{{sfn|Matić|Vesović|1995|p=73}} It was edited by the Executive Board of the CNK, mainly by dr. Đura Đurović who was board's secretary in period between June and September{{sfn|Buchenau|2004|p=77}} 1944.{{sfn|Matić|Vesović|1995|p=73}}
== Final days == Facing the entrance of pro-Partisan Communist [[Red Army]] troops into Axis occupied Yugoslavia the CNK reached decision to follow advices received from the USA to gather their forces in [[Banja Luka]] and wait for invasion of Allied forces on Dalmatian coast and their infiltration into Bosnia and other parts of Yugoslavia. On 21 February 1945 [[Pavle Đurišić]] organized a conference and concluded that they should retreat to Slovenia until more favorable political situation for their national cause is reached, inviting Mihailović and CNK to follow their conclusions.{{sfn|Pajović|Željeznov|Božović|1987|p=91}} In the absence of the reply from Mihailović on 1 March 1945 Đurišić organized new broader conference of the "National Committee of Higher Military Commanders and Intellectuals from Montenegro, Boka and Old Ras" with the same conclusions.{{sfn|Pajović|Željeznov|Božović|1987|p=91}} Mihailović and CNK rejected decisions of this conference and condemned Đurišić.{{sfn|Kovačević|1993|p=81|ps=: " ... извијестио да Врховна команда и Централни национални комитет не прихватају и осуђују самозвану Ђуришићеву ..."}}
Some members of the CNK, including its president [[Dragiša Vasić]], joined Đurišić and began their journey toward Slovenia, contrary to the decisions of Mihailović. After the [[Battle of Lijevče Field]] they were all captured and together with Đurišić and other captured Chetnik officers taken to [[Jasenovac death camp]] where they were all killed in April 1945.{{sfn|Čengić|1985|p=183}}
== Consequences == Many authors emphasize that [[Stevan Moljević]] and his work [[Homogeneous Serbia]] had crucialy important role in preparation of a coherent set of Chetnik war objectives with establishment of the [[Greater Serbia]] as one of the most important Chetnik war objectives. [[John R. Lampe]] pointed to secondary status of the Central National Committee and Moljević rising to prominence in this committee only in 1943, as significant details that undercut the perception about Moljević's "[[Homogeneous Serbia]]" being the centerpiece of coherent set of Chetnik war objectives.{{sfn|Lampe|2000|p=206}}
