[[File:Dr. Dan Kammen, UC Berkeley (14996536218) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Kammen in 2014]]
'''Daniel Merson Kammen''' is a Distinguished Professor of Energy in the Energy and Resources Group at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] and a former Science Envoy for the [[State Department]].<ref name="agrion">{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2016/02/253734.htm|title=State Department : Announcement of U.S. Science Envoys}}</ref><ref name=sacbee/> He holds a dual appointment at the University's Energy and Resources Group (part of the [[University of California, Berkeley College of Natural Resources|College of Natural Resources]]) and the [[Goldman School of Public Policy]]. He is also a coordinating lead author for the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]], which won the 2007 [[Nobel Peace Prize]] for their report, ''[[Climate Change 2007]]'', assessing man-made [[global warming]].<ref name="ccc">{{cite web|url=http://www.copenhagenclimatecouncil.com/about-us/councillors/daniel-m-kammen.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105212342/http://www.copenhagenclimatecouncil.com/about-us/councillors/daniel-m-kammen.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2009-01-05 |title=Daniel M. Kammen - Copenhagen Climate Council |publisher=[[Copenhagen Climate Council]] |accessdate=2010-03-04 }}</ref> Kammen was elected a permanent [[fellow#Honorary fellow|fellow]] of the [[African Academy of Sciences]] in 1998 and, in 2007, received the Distinguished Citizen Award from the [[Commonwealth Club of California]].<ref name="ccc"/>
On September 9, 2010, Kammen was appointed chief technical specialist for [[renewable energy]] and energy efficiency at the [[World Bank]].<ref name=recharge120710> {{cite news |url= http://www.rechargenews.com/business_area/politics/article228991.ece |title= World Bank names California professor as clean energy chief |newspaper = ReCharge | publisher = NHST Media Group | first = Richard A. | last = Kessler |date=2010-09-10 |accessdate=2010-09-11}} </ref>
In 2016, he was selected as a U.S. Science Envoy by the [[United States State Department]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Announcement of U.S. Science Envoys|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2016/02/253734.htm|accessdate=August 24, 2017|work=United States Department of State|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref> He resigned from this position in 2017, citing what he believed to be President Trump's failure to denounce white supremacists and neo-nazis.<ref name=sacbee>{{cite news|title=Prominent UC professor resigns post in Trump administration|url=http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article168775527.html|work=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|date=August 23, 2017}}</ref> His August 23, 2017, resignation letter went viral, as netizens noticed that the first letter of each paragraph spelled out I-M-P-E-A-C-H.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's science envoy quits in scathing letter with an embedded message: I-M-P-E-A-C-H |author=Amy B Wang |date=August 23, 2017 |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2017/08/23/trumps-science-envoy-quits-with-scathing-letter-with-an-embedded-message-i-m-p-e-a-c-h/}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Originally from [[Ithaca, New York]], Kammen is the son of [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning historian and Cornell University professor [[Michael Kammen]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/michael-kammen-pulitzer-winning-historian-dies-at-77/2013/12/04/90374b28-5d00-11e3-95c2-13623eb2b0e1_story.html | title=Michael Kammen, Pulitzer-winning historian, dies at 77 | work=The Washington Post | date=December 4, 2013 | accessdate=November 15, 2014 | author=Schudel, Matt}}</ref> He received his [[bachelor]]'s degree in [[physics]] from [[Cornell University]] and his [[master's degree]] and [[PhD]] in physics from [[Harvard University]].<ref name=CV>{{cite web|last1=Kammen|first1=Daniel|title=Kammen CV|url=http://kammen.berkeley.edu/DMK-CV-9.23.pdf|accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref> As a postdoctoral researcher at [[Caltech]], Kammen began to transition to energy research, with a focus on the role of energy in developing economies.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Raphael|first1=Chris|title=Dan Kammen's race against climate change|url=https://www.aaas.org/blog/member-spotlight/dan-kammens-race-against-climate-change|accessdate=April 6, 2018}}</ref>
